{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Dynamical Decoupling\n",
    "\n",
    "<p>\n",
    "<font size=4 color=\"#0f62fe\">IBM Quantum Enabling Technologies Team</font>\n",
    "<p>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Information is futile in the Quantum world. Any operation on qubits, as well as qubits just sitting idle, are subject to noise. [Decoherence](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_decoherence) and [Dephasing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dephasing) effects are driving qubits towards more classical [Mixed states](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_state#Mixed_states). A common technique in Quantum Information Processing in order to prevent these effects is [Dynamical Decoupling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamical_decoupling). We use Dynamical Decoupling in its simplest form, by implementing periodic sequences of gates, which serve to average out unwanted system-enviroment couplings. We focus on decoupling qubits that are idle for some time during a quantum circuit. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\n",
    "Note that the optimal dynamical decoupling strategy depends largely on the involved specific backend and the circuits & algorithms used. The strategies used here should therefore not be seen as 'cooking recipe' but as experimental work which needs to be adapted to the specific situation of your problem and the real hardware you use.\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "Qiskit offers an in-built [`PadDynamicalDecoupling`](https://qiskit.org/documentation/stubs/qiskit.transpiler.passes.PadDynamicalDecoupling.html) class which allows to fill gaps in quantum circuits with a dynamical decoupling sequence for noise reduction. In order to use it, a pulse schedule needs to be defined by a `PassManager` applied to your circuit. `PadDynamicalDecoupling` scans the circuit for idle periods of time and inserts a sequence of gates in those spots. These gates amount to the identity, so do they not change the circuit per se and its outcomes, but have the effect of mitigating noise in those idle periods. We will also look at tools from [qiskit-research](https://github.com/qiskit-research/qiskit-research) which allow to apply Dynamical Decoupling more easily and have a greater varity of sequences and gates."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Frontmatter\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we load the modules needed for the rest of the notebook, our IBM Quantum account and the real backend we'll use."
   ]
  },

   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},

    "from qiskit import *\n",

    "from qiskit.circuit.library import XGate\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler import PassManager, InstructionDurations\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler.passes import ALAPScheduleAnalysis, PadDynamicalDecoupling\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import hellinger_fidelity\n",
    "\n",
    "#for illustration of backend & qiskit version table\n",
    "import qiskit.tools.jupyter\n",
    "\n",

    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina'"

   ]
  },
  {

    "circ = QuantumCircuit(4)\n",
    "circ.h(0)\n",
    "circ.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "circ.cx(1, 2)\n",
    "circ.cx(2, 3)\n",
    "circ.measure_all()\n",
    "# \n",
    "durations = InstructionDurations(\n",
    "    [\n",
    "        (\"h\", 0, 50), \n",
    "        (\"cx\", [0, 1], 700), \n",
    "        (\"cx\", [1, 2], 200), \n",
    "        (\"cx\", [2, 3], 300),\n",
    "        (\"measure\", None, 1000),\n",

    "### Applying Dynamical Decoupling"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We use `PadDynamicalDecoupling` inside a `PassManager` to add a Decoupling sequence to qubits at idle times. In this case, we use a simple X-X sequence. Note that some backends have different timing constraints, depending on the version of Room Temperature Electronics (control electronics) gateware they run on. This was one of the reasons, `PadDynamicalDecoupling` was recently introduced as a replacement of the previous `DynamicalDecoupling` method, besides improvements in scheduling. There are subtle differences in timing constraints, compare for example the `pulse_alignment` for the following two backends"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "ibm_cairo\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'acquire_alignment': 16,\n",
       " 'granularity': 16,\n",
       " 'min_length': 64,\n",
       " 'pulse_alignment': 1}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 8,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(backend.name())\n",
    "backend.configuration().timing_constraints"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'acquire_alignment': 16,\n",
       " 'granularity': 16,\n",
       " 'min_length': 64,\n",
       " 'pulse_alignment': 16}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "provider.backend.ibm_washington.configuration().timing_constraints"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In order to account for this difference, we include information on pulse alignment to the `PadDynamicalDecoupling` method inside the `PassManager` as we set up to run on the backend."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",

       "<Figure size 899.479x325.08 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 32,
     "metadata": {

    }

   "source": [
    "# balanced X-X sequence on all qubits\n",
    "dd_sequence = [XGate(), XGate()]\n",
    "\n",
    "pm = PassManager(\n",
    "    [\n",
    "        ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations),\n",
    "        PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations, dd_sequence, \n",
    "        pulse_alignment=backend.configuration().timing_constraints['pulse_alignment'])\n",
    "    ]\n",
    "    )\n",
    "circ_dd = pm.run(circ)\n",
    "circ_dd.draw()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Varying gate spacing"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "`PadDynamicalDecoupling` allows to vary the time between the dynamical decoupling gates by specifing the parameter `spacing`. One way of doing so was given by Prof. Uhrig of TU Dortmund in his paper [Keeping a Quantum Bit Alive by Optimized -Pulse Sequences](https://arxiv.org/abs/quant-ph/0609203). We can apply his method in the following way"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Uhrig sequence on qubit 0\n",
    "n = 8\n",
    "dd_sequence = [XGate()] * n\n",
    "def uhrig_pulse_location(k):\n",
    "    return np.sin(np.pi * (k + 1) / (2 * n + 2)) ** 2\n",
    "spacing = []\n",
    "for k in range(n):\n",
    "    spacing.append(uhrig_pulse_location(k) - sum(spacing))\n",
    "spacing.append(1 - sum(spacing))\n",
    "\n",
    "pm = PassManager(\n",
    "    [\n",
    "        ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations),\n",
    "        PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations, dd_sequence, qubits=[0], spacing=spacing,\n",
    "        pulse_alignment=backend.configuration().timing_constraints['pulse_alignment']),\n",
    "    ]\n",
    ")\n",
    "circ_dd_uhrig = pm.run(circ)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1763.2x325.08 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 20,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 285,
       "width": 1442
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circ_dd_uhrig_transpiled=transpile(circ_dd_uhrig, backend, \n",
    "    scheduling_method=\"alap\",initial_layout=[[23,24,25,22]])\n",
    "circ_dd_uhrig_transpiled.draw(idle_wires=False,fold=-1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note the varying times of the Delay instructions and the fact that more gates were included as compared to the previous implementation just above"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 76,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dd_job_uhrig = backend.run(circ_dd_uhrig_transpiled)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us compare the different results by looking at counts and the [Hellinger Fidelities](https://qiskit.org/documentation/stubs/qiskit.quantum_info.hellinger_fidelity.html) of the probability distributions as compared to the simulation. The Hellinger fidelity quantifies the similiarity between two probability distributions in terms of their [Hellinger distance](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hellinger_distance) and is 1 in the ideal case of two agreeing probability distributions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "simulated_counts=sim_job.result().get_counts()\n",
    "counts=job.result().get_counts()\n",
    "dd_counts = dd_job.result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 80,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",

      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 80,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {

      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dd_counts_uhrig = dd_job_uhrig.result().get_counts()\n",
    "plot_histogram([simulated_counts,counts,dd_counts,dd_counts_uhrig], \n",
    "legend=['simulated counts','original counts','dynamically decoupled counts','DD using Uhrig spacing'])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 81,
   "metadata": {},

   "source": [

    "    hellinger_fidelity(simulated_counts,dd_counts),\n",
    "    hellinger_fidelity(simulated_counts,dd_counts_uhrig)\n",
    "    ]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Hellinger fidelity')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('list index')\n",
    "plt.title('0: original circuit \\n 1: dynamically decoupled \\n 2: Uhrig spacing')\n",
    "plt.plot(fidelities);"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that Dynamical Decoupling does have effects on the performance of this basic GHZ circuit, however the dynamical decoupling method needs to be carefully chosen."
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "## Decoupling a mid-circuit measurement"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Measurements take up quite some time in the course of a circuit. Let us see the effects of applying dynamical decoupling during a measurement & reset sequence. This circuit is inspired by the IBM research blog's [introduction](https://www.ibm.com/blogs/research/2021/02/quantum-mid-circuit-measurement/) of mid-circuit measurements."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

   "source": [
    "circ_mid_meas = QuantumCircuit(2,3)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.h(1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.cx(1, 0)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.h(1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.measure(1,2)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.barrier(0,1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.reset(1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.measure(0,0)\n",
    "circ_mid_meas.measure(1,1)\n",
    "\n",
    "#durations can also be obtained directly from the specific backend\n",

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We also compare with a version of the circuit in which all qubits get dynamically decoupled, even if they are not part of the active circuit at all. We do this by setting `skip_reset_qubits=False` inside `PadDynamicalDecoupling`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1183.47x1709.68 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 21,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1406,
       "width": 973
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dd_sequence = [XGate(), XGate()]\n",
    "pm_skipfalse = PassManager([ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations_backend),\n",
    "                  PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations_backend, dd_sequence,skip_reset_qubits=False,\n",
    "                  pulse_alignment=backend.configuration().timing_constraints['pulse_alignment'])])\n",
    "circ_dd_midmeas_skipfalse = pm_skipfalse.run(circ_mid_meas_transp)\n",
    "circ_dd_midmeas_skipfalse.draw(idle_wires=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "job_dd_midmeas_skipfalse=backend.run(circ_dd_midmeas_skipfalse)"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that Dynamical Decoupling is beneficial in general, however applying extra pulses to passive qubits was not successful in this case. There can be cases in which spectator qubits play an important role, however, which is when decoupling on all qubits can be beneficial."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Application to Bernstein-Vazirani"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The [Bernstein-Vazirani Algorithm](https://qiskit.org/textbook/ch-algorithms/bernstein-vazirani.html) is a modification of the Deutsch-Josza algorithm. It is constructed to learn a string encoded in a function. Its circuits turn out to possess long idle times and have thus [shown to be well-suited](https://gist.github.com/blakejohnson/9d0d7aa8c50350f869ed3eeca185f8f0) for an application of the kind of dynamical decoupling presented. Let us look at this effect in a concise manner. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Setting up the circuit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def create_oracle(num_qubits, input_size, secret_int):\n",
    "    # Initialize first n qubits and single ancilla qubit\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(num_qubits, name=f\"Uf\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # perform CX for each qubit that matches a bit in secret string\n",
    "    s = ('{0:0' + str(input_size) + 'b}').format(secret_int)\n",
    "    for i_qubit in range(input_size):\n",
    "        if s[input_size - 1 - i_qubit] == '1':\n",
    "            qc.cx(i_qubit, input_size)\n",
    "    return qc\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def bernstein_vazirani(num_qubits, secret_int):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # size of input is one less than available qubits\n",
    "    input_size = num_qubits - 1\n",
    "\n",
    "    # setup circuit\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(num_qubits, input_size, name=\"main\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # put ancilla in |1> state\n",
    "    qc.x(input_size)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # start with Hadamard on all qubits, including ancilla\n",
    "    for i_qubit in range(num_qubits):\n",
    "         qc.h(i_qubit)\n",
    "\n",
    "    qc.barrier()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # generate Uf oracle\n",
    "    Uf = create_oracle(num_qubits, input_size, secret_int)\n",
    "    qc.append(Uf, range(num_qubits))\n",
    "\n",
    "    qc.barrier()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Hadamard again on all non-ancilla qubits,\n",
    "    for i_qubit in range(input_size):\n",
    "         qc.h(i_qubit)\n",
    "\n",
    "    qc.barrier()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # measure all data qubits\n",
    "    for i in range(input_size):\n",
    "        qc.measure(i, i)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return qc"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 748.797x385.28 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 23,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 326,
       "width": 620
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "bv_circuit_test = bernstein_vazirani(5, int('1101', 2))\n",
    "bv_circuit_test.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "### Apply Dynamical Decoupling"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "durations_backend = InstructionDurations.from_backend(backend)\n",
    "dd_sequence = [XGate(), XGate()]\n",
    "pm = PassManager([ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations_backend),\n",
    "                  PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations_backend, dd_sequence,\n",
    "                  pulse_alignment=backend.configuration().timing_constraints['pulse_alignment'])])\n",
    "\n",
    "# transpile and view the resulting circuit\n",
    "circ_dd_bv = pm.run(bv_transpiled)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "metadata": {},

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Apply Dynamical Decoupling more easily and have a greater varity of sequences"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We saw that managing `PassManager`, scheduling and chosing the right methods for transpiling are somewhat involved. Luckily there are people working on making life easier for you as a user at [qiskit-research](https://github.com/qiskit-research/qiskit-research) . A useful utility in this context is the method `add_dynamical_decoupling`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Install qiskit-research by running \n",
    "```\n",
    "git clone https://github.com/qiskit-research/qiskit-research.git\n",
    "cd qiskit-research\n",
    "pip install .\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 800x325.08 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 18,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 285,
       "width": 662
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circuit_transpiled=transpile(circ,backend=backend,initial_layout=[[23,24,25,22]])\n",
    "circuit_transpiled.draw(idle_wires=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "`add_dynamical_decoupling` makes it easy to add sepcific DD sequences to a circuit that is transpiled to match the gate definitions of the backend. It also gives you the option to specify a string of which sequence you would like to add. At the time of writing, the following sequences are available:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dd_sequences= [\"X2\",\"XY4\",\"XY8\",\"X2pm\",\"XY4pm\",\"XY8pm\"]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that the suffix `\"pm\"` indicates plus, minus and refers to rotations with positive or negative sign, respectively. At the microwave pulse level, this corresponds to the sign of the amplitude. The circuit below shows an example of a `\"X2pm\"` decoupling sequence."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 43,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080.08x1709.68 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 43,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1399,
       "width": 889
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from qiskit_research.utils.convenience import add_dynamical_decoupling\n",
    "\n",
    "circ_with_dd = add_dynamical_decoupling(circuit_transpiled, backend, \"X2pm\", add_pulse_cals=False)\n",
    "circ_with_dd.draw()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So let us compare the effects of different sequences added to the original GHZ circuit. Note that we need to input a transpiled circuit to the `add_dynamical_decoupling` method, such that the right basis gates and instruction durations are provided. Here, we also transpile again after adding dynamical decoupling since some of the gates involved are not part of the basis gate set. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [

   "execution_count": 40,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dd_circuits=[]\n",
    "for sequence in dd_sequences:\n",
    "    dd_circuits.append(\n",
    "        transpile(\n",
    "        add_dynamical_decoupling(circuit_transpiled, backend, sequence, add_pulse_cals=False)\n",
    "        ,backend,scheduling_method=\"alap\")\n",
    "    )"
   ]

    "ax.set_title('Hellinger fidelities of Dynamical Decoupling sequences')\n",
    "ax.set_ylim([np.min(fidelities2)*0.999, max(fidelities2)*1.001])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So we already see that there may be better sequences than X-X, depending on the circuit in question. However, why do the `\"pm\"` sequences perform so poorly in terms of Hellinger fidelity? Let us see what the second transpilation did to the circuit with the `\"X2pm\"` sequence applied."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1114.27x1709.68 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 31,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 1399,
       "width": 916
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "transpile(circ_with_dd,backend,scheduling_method=\"alap\").draw()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So the `\"Xp\"` and `\"Xm\"` gates were transpiled back to basis gates again. Instead, if we want to use those gates as intended, we have to specify the option `add_pulse_cals=True` within `add_dynamical_decoupling`. The method will take care of defining those gates for us at the Pulse level. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dd_circuits_cals=[]\n",
    "for sequence in dd_sequences:\n",
    "    dd_circuits_cals.append(\n",
    "        add_dynamical_decoupling(circuit_transpiled, backend, sequence, add_pulse_cals=True)\n",
    "    )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "job_dd_cals = backend.run(dd_circuits_cals)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As an example, the circuit now looks like this with the `\"XY4pm\"` sequence added "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

      ]
     },

      }

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "These tricks can increase the performance of our circuit run on the backend by quite a bit. Note how the sequences containing custom gates `\"XY*\"` as well as the `\"*pm\"` sequences improve in performance relative to `\"X2\"`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {

       "height": 481,
       "width": 636
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "simulated_counts=sim_job.result().get_counts()\n",
    "\n",
    "hellinger_function = lambda x: hellinger_fidelity(simulated_counts,x)\n",
    "\n",
    "fidelities3 = list(map(hellinger_function,\n",
    "    job_dd_cals.result().get_counts()))\n",
    "\n",
    "fidelities_dict3=dict(zip(dd_sequences,fidelities3))\n",
    "plot_histogram(fidelities_dict3)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = plt.figure()\n",
    "ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])\n",
    "ax.bar(dd_sequences,fidelities3)\n",
    "ax.set_title('Hellinger fidelities of Dynamical Decoupling sequences')\n",
    "ax.set_ylim([min(fidelities3)*0.999, max(fidelities3)*1.001])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's confirm this observation statistically by running the same experiment with 100 circuits and 100.000 shots for each dynamical decoupling sequence applied to our exemplary GHZ circuit and compare against a circuit with no dynamical decoupling applied."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sequences=dd_sequences+dd_sequences+['no_dd']\n",
    "#initializing a dictonary for jobs for all sequences + the circuit with no dynamical decoupling applied\n",
    "job_dict=dict(zip(sequences,range(len(sequences))))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's run all these jobs on the backend (this will take a while)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dd_circuits_statistics=[]\n",
    "for sequence in dd_sequences:\n",
    "    circ_sequence=add_dynamical_decoupling(circuit_transpiled, backend, sequence, add_pulse_cals=True)\n",
    "    job_dict[sequence]=backend.run([circ_sequence]*100, shots=backend.configuration().max_shots)\n",
    "    job_dict[sequence].update_tags(additional_tags=[sequence,\"dynamical decoupling\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "job_dict['no_dd']=backend.run([circuit_transpiled]*100, shots=backend.configuration().max_shots)\n",
    "job_dict['no_dd'].update_tags(additional_tags=['no_dd']);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "After the 70.000.000 shots finished running, we collect Hellinger fidelities for each of the circuits"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fidelities_all = dict(zip(sequences,range(len(sequences))))\n",
    "for sequence in job_dict:\n",
    "    fidelities_all[sequence]=\n",
    "    list(map(hellinger_function,\n",
    "    job_dict[sequence].result().get_counts()))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 481,
       "width": 636
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig = plt.figure()\n",
    "ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])\n",
    "for sequence in fidelities_all:\n",
    "    ax.plot([sequence]*100,fidelities_all[sequence],'o')\n",
    "ax.set_title('Hellinger fidelities of dd sequences, 100 circuits at 100.000 shots each')\n",
    "ax.set_ylim([min(min(fidelities_all.values()))*0.999,max(max(fidelities_all.values()))*1.001])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This confirms that X2pm is the best sequence in this case. Note that the circuit without dynamical decoupling applied, at the right side of the plot above, performs comparably. As mentioned at the beginning of this guide, if and how to apply dynamical decoupling has to be analyzed on a case-by-case basis depending on the circuit and backend in question. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In Summary, we are provided with tools to easily add dynamical decoupling to our circuit and increase its Fidelity with gates defined at the Qiskit Pulse level. \n",
    "\n",
    "We see that using custom gates defined at Qiskit Pulse level is beneficial as compared to transpilation to the basis gates. This observation is confirmed in the literature, c.f. the recent arxiv [Dynamical decoupling for superconducting qubits: a performance survey](https://arxiv.org/abs/2207.03670), in particular Appendix B. There is ongoing work of extending the sequences available for dynamical decoupling at the pulse level, including the higher-order sequences discussed in the referenced paper."
   ]
  },
